  <refentry xml:id="r.installRuby" m:refclass="s:TaskDefinition">
    <!-- not so much a tool definition as much as a task definition -->
    <refnamediv>
      <refname>Install &ps.ruby; and
      <productname>RubyGems</productname></refname>
      <refpurpose>Program Tools Installation</refpurpose>
      <refclass>Task Definition</refclass>
    </refnamediv>
    <refsect1>
      <title>Summary</title>

      <para>The exact installation process for
      &ps.ruby; naturally will vary by host
      machine platform</para>

      <para>
	Once &ps.ruby; is installed, it may be
	recommended to use a package management system unique to
	&ps.ruby;, such as <productname
	xlink:href="https://rvm.io/rvm">RVM</productname> or
	<productname
	    xlink:href="https://github.com/sstephenson/rbenv"
	    >rbenv</productname>.
      </para>


      <refsect2>
	<title>Installing &ps.ruby; on &ps.linux; Platforms</title>

	<para>
	  The process for installing &ps.ruby; on the &ps.linux;
	  platform will depend on the nature of the &ps.linux;
	  <glossterm>distribution</glossterm> in use on the
	  <glossterm>host</glossterm>
	  <glossterm>machine</glossterm>. Typically, a
	  &ps.linux; <glossterm>distribution</glossterm> will feature
	  an integrated <glossterm>package manager</glossterm>, and a
	  <glossterm>graphical user interface</glossterm> for
	  accessing that <glossterm>package manager</glossterm>,
	  whether via a <glossterm>command line</glossterm>
	  <glossterm>terminal</glossterm> or alternately,
	  a graphical <glossterm>desktop</glossterm>  interface.
	</para>

	<refsect3>
	  <title>&ps.debian;: Packages for &ps.ruby; Platform
	  Component Installation</title>

	  <para>
	    A <glossterm>virtual package</glossterm>
	    named <symbol>ruby-interpreter</symbol> is available
	    on &ps.debian; &ps.linux;. The
	    <symbol>ruby-interpreter</symbol> <glossterm>virtual
	    package</glossterm> is <glossterm>provided</glossterm> by
	    any version-named package in the <glossterm>package
	    repository</glossterm>providing a &ps.ruby;
	    <glossterm>interpreter</glossterm>. Alternately, a
	    <glossterm>virtual package</glossterm> is available, named
	    <symbol>ruby-full</symbol>, such that effectively
	    depends on a broader set of packages for the
	    &ps.ruby; platform.
	  </para>

	  <para>
	    Additionally, the <symbol>rubygems</symbol> package should
	    be installed &mdash; optionally along with
	    <symbol>rubygems-doc</symbol> &mdash; as to be able to
	    install the  <symbol>rhc</symbol> gem for &ps.ruby;, via
	    the <command>gem</command> command. Note, however, that
	    the <symbol>rubygems</symbol> package may depend on a
	    specific version of &ps.ruby;, such that may be older than
	    the most recently released version. There is also the
	    <symbol>ruby-switch</symbol> package, for developing on
	    mutliple versions of the &ps.ruby; interpreter.
	  </para>

	  <para>
	    Lastly, the package,
	    <glossterm>rubygems-integration</glossterm> would be
	    recommended, as in order to ensure that &ps.debian;
	    packaged &ps.ruby; components, when installed,
	    will be visible to <productname>RubyGems</productname>.
	  </para>

	  <programlisting>sudo aptitude install rubygems rubygems-doc \
	  rubygems-integration ruby-switch</programlisting>

	</refsect3>
      </refsect2>

      <refsect2>
	<title>Installing &ps.ruby; on &ps.osx; Platforms</title>

	<para>
	  If &ps.ruby; is not available on the &ps.osx;
	  <glossterm>machine</glossterm>, it may be installed via
	  <productname xlink:href="https://developer.apple.com/xcode/"
		       >Xcode</productname>.
	</para>
      </refsect2>

      <refsect2>
	<title>Installing &ps.ruby; on &ps.mswin; Platforms</title>

	<para>
	  Refer to <productname
	  xlink:href="http://rubyinstaller.org/"
	  >RubyInstaller</productname>
	  for <productname>Windows</productname><citation><xref
	  linkend="b.installRuby.dlRuby"/></citation>. (Note that
	  <productname>RubyGems</productname> is distributed within
	  <productname>RubyInstaller</productname><citation><xref
	  linkend="b.installRuby.ari"/></citation>)
	</para>
      </refsect2>
